{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Oracle decimal scaling is ignored, so non-18-decimal feeds misprice collateral by orders of magnitude","locations":["src/interfaces/IOracle.sol:5","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:176"],"claim":"The pair hardcodes exchange-rate inversion as `1e36 / oraclePrice` and never normalizes by `IOracle.decimals()`, even though the oracle interface exposes a decimals field and `setOracle()` accepts arbitrary replacement feeds. Any oracle returning prices in a scale other than 18 decimals will distort the collateral/debt conversion by a power-of-ten factor.","impact":"Borrow, solvency, redemption, and liquidation math can all be wrong by orders of magnitude. Depending on the oracle scale, healthy positions can be liquidated or blocked from withdrawing, or collateral can be overvalued enough for borrowers to mint far more debt than intended, leaving the pair insolvent.","paths":["A pair is deployed with, or later updated to, an oracle whose `getPrices()` output is not 18-decimal scaled.","`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `exchangeRate = 1e36 / price` without using `IOracle.decimals()`.","The distorted exchange rate propagates into `_isSolvent()`, borrow limits, redemptions, and liquidations."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Unchecked Convex staking results can leave credited collateral unstaked and later lock withdrawals/liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:409","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:713","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:769"],"claim":"When Convex mode is enabled, the pair credits user collateral first and then calls `IConvexStaking.deposit(...)` without checking its boolean return value. `totalCollateral()` only counts the reward-contract stake balance, so if a Convex deposit returns `false` or stakes less than expected, the pair's accounting assumes collateral was staked while later exits try to withdraw shares that never reached Convex.","impact":"User collateral can become effectively stuck: withdrawals, liquidations, or pool migrations can revert because `_unstakeUnderlying()` pulls from the reward contract while the missing collateral remains idle in the pair. This creates accounting divergence and can permissionlessly DoS collateral exits for affected positions.","paths":["A borrower adds collateral while `convexPid != 0`, or the owner migrates pools with `_updateConvexPool()`.","The Convex `deposit(..., true)` call returns `false` or under-stakes, but the pair ignores the result and still keeps the higher `_userCollateralBalance`.","Later `_removeCollateral()` or pool migration calls `_unstakeUnderlying()` for the credited amount, but the reward contract balance is lower than expected, causing the operation to fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Collateral is released and debt is written off before redemption/liquidation settlement is verified","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`redeemCollateral()` and `liquidate()` are explicitly restricted to registry-configured handler contracts. The missing local settlement check is a trusted-module assumption about privileged handlers, not a permissionless pair-level exploit supported by the code alone."},{"title":"Share refactors leave `currentRateInfo.lastShares` stale across epochs","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`currentRateInfo.lastShares` is initialized from `IERC4626(_collateral).convertToShares(1e18)` and passed to the rate calculator as collateral-vault share data, not borrow-share supply. Borrow-share refactoring during redemption therefore does not make this value stale in the way claimed."},{"title":"Raw oracle responses are accepted without zero, freshness, or sanity checks","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Aside from the separate decimal-normalization bug, this report mostly describes oracle-layer failures or trust assumptions. A zero/stale/manipulated price would come from the configured oracle itself, and the code does not show that the pair is expected to enforce freshness/deviation validation independently."}]}
